07620nam a22010335i 9780823298631DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232986317 a10.1515/97808232986312doi  a(DE-B1597)612812  a(OCoLC)1273001440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0490002bisacsh04a248.4/81522300aWomen and Religiosity in Orthodox Christianity /ced. by Ina Merdjanova. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b4 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOrthodox Christianity and Contemporary Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tWomen in Orthodox Chris tian ity: A Foreword -- tIntroduction -- tContributors -- tWomen and Greek Orthodoxy in the TwentyFirst Century: Charting Ele ments of Change -- tWomen, Orthodox Chris tian ity, and Neosecularization in Bulgaria -- tLay Women and the Transformation of Orthodox Chris tian ity in Rus sia -- tWomen and the Georgian Orthodox Church -- tWomen and Orthodox Dissent: The Case of the Archangelist Under ground Movement in Soviet Moldavia -- tGender and Religiosity in Communist Romania: Continuity and Change -- tDoubly Neglected: Histories of Women Monastics in the Serbian Orthodox Church -- tWomen as Agents of Glocalization in the Orthodox Church of Finland -- tHead Coverings, Vaccines, and Gender Politics: Contentious Topics among Orthodox Christian Women in USbased Digital Spaces -- tAcknowl edgments -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen and Religiosity in Orthodox Christianity fills a significant gap in the sociology of religious practice: Studies focused on women’s religiosity have overlooked Orthodox populations, while studies of Orthodox practice (operating within the dominant theological, historical, and sociological framework) have remained gender-blind.The essays in this collection shed new light on the women who make up a considerable majority of the Orthodox population by engaging women’s lifeworlds, practices, and experiences in relation to their religion in multiple, varied localities, discussing both contemporary and pre-1989 developments. These contributions critically engage the pluralist and changing character of Orthodox institutional and social life by using feminist epistemologies and drawing on original ethnographic research to account for Orthodox women’s previously ignored perspectives, knowledges, and experiences.Combining the depth of ethnographic analysis with geographical breadth and employing a variety of research methodologies, this book expands our understanding of Orthodox Christianity by examining Orthodox women of diverse backgrounds in different settings: parishes, monasteries, and the secular spaces of everyday life, and under shifting historical conditions and political regimes. In defiance of claims that Orthodox Christianity is immutable and fixed in time, these essays argue that continuity and transformation can be found harmoniously in social practices, demographic trends, and larger material contexts at the intersection between gender, Orthodoxy, and locality.Contributors: Kristin Aune, Milica Bakić-Hayden, Maria Bucur, Ketevan Gurchiani, James Kapaló, Helena Kupari, Ina Merdjanova, Sarah Riccardi-Swartz, Eleni Sotiriou, Tatiana Tiaynen-Qadir, Detelina Tocheva  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aChristian womenxReligious life. 0aWomen in the Orthodox Eastern Church. 4aAnthropology. 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Orthodox.2bisacsh  aOrthodox Christianity.  aOrthodox Church.  acontinuity.  agender.  areligiosity.  atransformation.  awomen.1 aAune